### Background: What the Codebase Tells Us

The project is an ESM TypeScript project (`"type": "module"`, `module: Node16`) with strict mode enabled. This has one hard consequence: all local imports require explicit `.js` extensions even when importing `.ts` source files. The new service files must follow this same convention.

The tests run end-to-end through the real Express app with no mocking, which means the refactor must be purely structural — the observable HTTP responses (status codes, body shapes) must be byte-for-byte identical. No new behavior is introduced.

The in-memory store in `src/data.ts` holds mutable arrays that are mutated in-place. The services will import these same arrays and mutate them the same way, so state is naturally shared.

